hould be denoted with suffix "e" (for "energetic") to avoid confusion with photometric or <a href="/wiki/Photon" title="Photon">photon</a> quantities.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-note-alternative-symbol-radiometric-20"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-radiometric_20-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-radiometric_20-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-radiometric_20-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-radiometric_20-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-radiometric_20-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Alternative symbols sometimes seen: <i>W</i> or <i>E</i> for radiant energy, <i>P</i> or <i>F</i> for radiant flux, <i>I</i> for irradiance, <i>W</i> for radiant&#160;exitance.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-note-suffix-nu-21"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-nu_21-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-nu_21-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-nu_21-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-nu_21-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-nu_21-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-nu_21-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-nu_21-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Spectral quantities given per unit <a href="/wiki/Frequency" title="Frequency">frequency</a> are denoted with suffix "<a href="/wiki/Nu_(letter)" title="Nu (letter)">\xce\xbd</a>" (Greek)\xe2\x80\x94not to be confused with suffix "v" (for "visual") indicating a photometric quantity.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-note-suffix-lambda-22"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-lambda_22-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-lambda_22-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-lambda_22-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-lambda_22-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-lambda_22-4"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-lambda_22-5"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-lambda_22-6"><sup><i><b>g</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Spectral quantities given per unit <a href="/wiki/Wavelength" title="Wavelength">wavelength</a> are denoted with suffix "<a href="/wiki/Lambda" title="Lambda">\xce\xbb</a>" (Greek).</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-note-suffix-omega-23"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-omega_23-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-omega_23-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Directional quantities are denoted with suffix "<a href="/wiki/Omega" title="Omega">\xce\xa9</a>" (Greek).</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-note-suffix-v-24"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-note-suffix-v_24-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/Standards_organization" title="Standards organization">Standards organizations</a> recommend that photometric quantities be denoted with a suffix "v" (for "visual") to avoid confusion with radiometric or <a href="/wiki/Photon" title="Photon">photon</a> quantities. For example: <i>USA Standard Letter Symbols for Illuminating Engineering</i> USAS Z7.1-1967, Y10.18-1967</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-note-alternative-symbol-photometric-25"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-photometric_25-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-photometric_25-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-alternative-symbol-photometric_25-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">Alternative symbols sometimes seen: <i>W</i> for luminous energy, <i>P</i> or <i>F</i> for luminous flux, and <i>\xcf\x81</i> or <i>K</i> for luminous efficacy.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-note-dimension-J-26"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-note-dimension-J_26-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-dimension-J_26-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-note-dimension-J_26-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text">"<b>J</b>" here is the symbol for the <a href="/wiki/Dimension_of_a_physical_quantity" class="mw-redirect" title="Dimension of a physical quantity">dimension</a> of luminous intensity, not the symbol for the <a href="/wiki/Units_of_measurement" title="Units of measurement">unit</a> joules.</span></li>\n</ol>\n</div>\n</div>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span></h2>\n<div class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">\n<ol class="references">\n<li id="cite_note-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/wiki/International_Commission_on_Illumination" title="International Commission on Illumination">CIE</a> (1987). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.cie.co.at/publ/abst/17-4-89.html"><i>International Lighting Vocabulary</i></a>. Number 17.4. CIE, 4th edition. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a> <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-3-900734-07-7" title="Special:BookSources/978-3-900734-07-7">978-3-900734-07-7</a>.<br />\nBy the <i>International Lighting Vocabulary</i>, the definition of <i>light</i> is: \xe2\x80\x9cAny radiation capable of causing a visual sensation directly.\xe2\x80\x9d</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Pal2001-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Pal2001_2-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Pal, G. K.; Pal, Pravati (2001). "chapter 52". <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=CcJvIiesqp8C&amp;pg=PA387"><i>Textbook of Practical Physiology</i></a> (1st ed.). Chennai: Orient Blackswan. p.&#160;387. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-81-250-2021-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-250-2021-9">978-81-250-2021-9</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">11 October</span> 2013</span>. <q>The human eye has the ability to respond to all the wavelengths of light from 400\xe2\x80\x93700 nm. This is called the visible part of the spectrum.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.atitle=chapter+52&amp;rft.au=Pal%2C+Pravati&amp;rft.aufirst=G.+K.&amp;rft.aulast=Pal&amp;rft.btitle=Textbook+of+Practical+Physiology&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.edition=1st&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.isbn=978-81-250-2021-9&amp;rft.pages=387&amp;rft.place=Chennai&amp;rft.pub=Orient+Blackswan&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DCcJvIiesqp8C%26pg%3DPA387&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-BuserImbert1992-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-BuserImbert1992_3-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Buser, Pierre A.; Imbert, Michel (1992). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=NSZvt8Ld2-8C&amp;pg=PA50"><i>Vision</i></a>. MIT Press. p.&#160;50. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-262-02336-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-262-02336-8">978-0-262-02336-8</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">11 October</span> 2013</span>. <q>Light is a special class of radiant energy embracing wavelengths between 400 and 700 nm (or m\xce\xbc), or 4000 to 7000 \xc3\x85.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.au=Imbert%2C+Michel&amp;rft.aufirst=Pierre+A.&amp;rft.aulast=Buser&amp;rft.btitle=Vision&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-262-02336-8&amp;rft.pages=50&amp;rft.pub=MIT+Press&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DNSZvt8Ld2-8C%26pg%3DPA50&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Gregory Hallock Smith (2006). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/?id=6mb0C0cFCEYC&amp;pg=PA4"><i>Camera lenses: from box camera to digital</i></a>. SPIE Press. p.&#160;4. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8194-6093-6" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8194-6093-6">978-0-8194-6093-6</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.au=Gregory+Hallock+Smith&amp;rft.btitle=Camera+lenses%3A+from+box+camera+to+digital&amp;rft.date=2006&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8194-6093-6&amp;rft.pages=4&amp;rft.pub=SPIE+Press&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3D6mb0C0cFCEYC%26pg%3DPA4&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Narinder Kumar (2008). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/?id=IryMtwHHngIC&amp;pg=PA1416"><i>Comprehensive Physics XII</i></a>. Laxmi Publications. p.&#160;1416. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-81-7008-592-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-7008-592-8">978-81-7008-592-8</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.au=Narinder+Kumar&amp;rft.btitle=Comprehensive+Physics+XII&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-81-7008-592-8&amp;rft.pages=1416&amp;rft.pub=Laxmi+Publications&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2F%3Fid%3DIryMtwHHngIC%26pg%3DPA1416&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Laufer, Gabriel (13 July 1996). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=4MxLPYMS5TUC&amp;pg=PA11"><i>Introduction to Optics and Lasers in Engineering</i></a>. Cambridge University Press. p.&#160;11. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-521-45233-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-521-45233-5">978-0-521-45233-5</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">20 October</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.aufirst=Gabriel&amp;rft.aulast=Laufer&amp;rft.btitle=Introduction+to+Optics+and+Lasers+in+Engineering&amp;rft.date=1996-07-13&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-521-45233-5&amp;rft.pages=11&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D4MxLPYMS5TUC%26pg%3DPA11&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Bradt2004-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Bradt2004_7-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Bradt, Hale (2004). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=hp7vyaGvhLMC&amp;pg=PA26"><i>Astronomy Methods: A Physical Approach to Astronomical Observations</i></a>. Cambridge University Press. p.&#160;26. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-521-53551-9" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-521-53551-9">978-0-521-53551-9</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">20 October</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.aufirst=Hale&amp;rft.aulast=Bradt&amp;rft.btitle=Astronomy+Methods%3A+A+Physical+Approach+to+Astronomical+Observations&amp;rft.date=2004&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-521-53551-9&amp;rft.pages=26&amp;rft.pub=Cambridge+University+Press&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dhp7vyaGvhLMC%26pg%3DPA26&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-OhannesianStreeter2001-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-OhannesianStreeter2001_8-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Ohannesian, Lena; Streeter, Anthony (9 November 2001). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=DwPb4wgqseYC&amp;pg=PA187"><i>Handbook of Pharmaceutical Analysis</i></a>. CRC Press. p.&#160;187. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-8247-4194-5" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-8247-4194-5">978-0-8247-4194-5</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">20 October</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.au=Streeter%2C+Anthony&amp;rft.aufirst=Lena&amp;rft.aulast=Ohannesian&amp;rft.btitle=Handbook+of+Pharmaceutical+Analysis&amp;rft.date=2001-11-09&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-8247-4194-5&amp;rft.pages=187&amp;rft.pub=CRC+Press&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DDwPb4wgqseYC%26pg%3DPA187&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-AhluwaliaGoyal2000-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-AhluwaliaGoyal2000_9-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Ahluwalia, V. K.; Goyal, Madhuri (1 January 2000). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=tJNJnn0M75MC&amp;pg=PA110"><i>A Textbook of Organic Chemistry</i></a>. Narosa. p.&#160;110. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-81-7319-159-6" title="Special:BookSources/978-81-7319-159-6">978-81-7319-159-6</a><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">20 October</span> 2013</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.au=Goyal%2C+Madhuri&amp;rft.aufirst=V.+K.&amp;rft.aulast=Ahluwalia&amp;rft.btitle=A+Textbook+of+Organic+Chemistry&amp;rft.date=2000-01-01&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-81-7319-159-6&amp;rft.pages=110&amp;rft.pub=Narosa&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DtJNJnn0M75MC%26pg%3DPA110&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Sliney1976-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Sliney1976_10-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Sliney, David H.; Wangemann, Robert T.; Franks, James K.; Wolbarsht, Myron L. (1976). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.opticsinfobase.org/josa/abstract.cfm?uri=josa-66-4-339">"Visual sensitivity of the eye to infrared laser radiation"</a>. <i><a href="/wiki/Journal_of_the_Optical_Society_of_America" title="Journal of the Optical Society of America">Journal of the Optical Society of America</a></i>. <b>66</b> (4): 339\xe2\x80\x93341. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1364%2FJOSA.66.000339">10.1364/JOSA.66.000339</a>. <span style="font-size:90%; color:#555">(Subscription required (<span title="The site requires a paid subscription to access this page." style="border-bottom:1px dotted;cursor:help">help</span>))</span>. <q>The foveal sensitivity to several near-infrared laser wavelengths was measured. It was found that the eye could respond to radiation at wavelengths at least as far as 1064 nm. A continuous 1064 nm laser source appeared red, but a 1060 nm pulsed laser source appeared green, which suggests the presence of second harmonic generation in the retina.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALight&amp;rft.atitle=Visual+sensitivity+of+the+eye+to+infrared+laser+radiation&amp;rft.au=Franks%2C+James+K.&amp;rft.au=Wangemann%2C+Robert+T.&amp;rft.au=Wolbarsht%2C+Myron+L.&amp;rft.aufirst=David+H.&amp;rft.aulast=Sliney&amp;rft.date=1976&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.issue=4&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+the+Optical+Society+of+America&amp;rft.pages=339-341&amp;rft.volume=66&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.opticsinfobase.org%2Fjosa%2Fabstract.cfm%3Furi%3Djosa-66-4-339&amp;rft_id=info%3A